{"title_page": "Saha (surname)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2016}}\n\n'''Saha''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09be}})  is a [[Bengali Hindu]] surname mostly residing in the Indian states of [[West Bengal]], [[Assam]], and [[Tripura]], as well as in [[Bangladesh]]. People with surname Saha are economically and socially influential among the Hindus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saha, and Bangladesh.surname|url=http://indiachildnames.com/surname.aspx?surname=Saha|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref> Various business communities use the title 'Saha' or 'Shaha'<ref>http://bn.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%A3%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%95 </ref> Several meanings of Saha include \u2018merchant\u2019, 'honest' and 'good'. The word Saha is derived from Sanskrit \"Sadhu\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Saha Name Meaning and Saha Family History at ancestry.co.uk|url=http://www.ancestry.co.uk/name-origin?surname=saha|website=Genealogy, Family Trees and Family History Records at Ancestry.co.uk|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Meghnad_Saha_with_his_assistant.jpg|thumb|[[Meghnad Saha]] Of [[Bengal Presidency]]]]\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Meghnad Saha]] \u2013 Indian astrophysicist best known for his development of the Saha equation, used to describe chemical and physical conditions in stars\n*[[Wriddhiman Saha]] \u2013 Indian cricketer\n*[[Proloy Saha]] \u2013 Indian footballer\n*[[Asit Kumar Saha]] \u2013 National level wrestler\n*[[Gopinath Saha]] \u2013 Bengali activist for Indian independence\n*[[Ranadaprasad Saha]] \u2013 Bangladeshi businessman and philanthropist\n*[[Surjit Saha]] \u2013 Indian television actor and model\n*[[Debojit Saha]] \u2013 Indian singer\n*[[Mousumi Saha]] \u2013 Indian actress in Bengali films and television\n*[[Anamika Saha]] \u2013 Indian actress in Bengali films\n*[[Arati Saha]] \u2013 Indian swimmer\n*[[Swapan Saha]] \u2013 Indian film director in Bengali movies\n*[[Ena Saha ]] \u2013 Indian film actress and model\n*[[Chandrima Shaha]] \u2013 Indian biologist\n*[[Ashim Saha]] \u2013 Bangladeshi poet\n*[[Arun Saha]] \u2013 Bangladeshi actor\n\n==See also==\n* [[Shah]]\n*[[Shah (surname)]]\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{surname|Saha}}\n\n[[Category:Bengali Hindu surnames]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2016}}\n\n'''Saha''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09be}})  is a [[Bengali Hindu]] surname mostly residing in the Indian states of [[West Bengal]], [[Assam]], and [[Tripura]], as well as in [[Bangladesh]]. People with surname Saha are economically and socially influential among the Hindus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saha, and Bangladesh.surname|url=http://indiachildnames.com/surname.aspx?surname=Saha|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref> Various business communities use the title 'Saha' or 'Shaha'<ref>http://bn.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%A3%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%95 </ref> Several meanings of Saha include \u2018merchant\u2019, 'honest' and 'good'. The word Saha is derived from Sanskrit \"Sadhu\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Saha Name Meaning and Saha Family History at ancestry.co.uk|url=http://www.ancestry.co.uk/name-origin?surname=saha|website=Genealogy, Family Trees and Family History Records at Ancestry.co.uk|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Meghnad_Saha_with_his_assistant.jpg|thumb|[[Meghnad Saha]] Of [[Bengal Presidency]]]]\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Meghnad Saha]] \u2013 Indian astrophysicist best known for his development of the Saha equation, used to describe chemical and physical conditions in stars\n*[[Wriddhiman Saha]] \u2013 Indian cricketer\n*[[Proloy Saha]] \u2013 Indian footballer\n*[[Asit Kumar Saha]] \u2013 National level wrestler\n*[[Gopinath Saha]] \u2013 Bengali activist for Indian independence\n*[[Ranadaprasad Saha]] \u2013 Bangladeshi businessman and philanthropist\n*[[Surjit Saha]] \u2013 Indian television actor and model\n*[[Debojit Saha]] \u2013 Indian singer\n*[[Mousumi Saha]] \u2013 Indian actress in Bengali films and television\n*[[Anamika Saha]] \u2013 Indian actress in Bengali films\n*[[Arati Saha]] \u2013 Indian swimmer\n*[[Swapan Saha]] \u2013 Indian film director in Bengali movies\n*[[Ena Saha ]] \u2013 Indian film actress and model\n*[[Chandrima Shaha]] \u2013 Indian biologist\n*[[Ashim Saha]] \u2013 Bangladeshi poet\n*[[Arun Saha]] \u2013 Bangladeshi actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{surname|Saha}}\n\n[[Category:Bengali Hindu surnames]]\n", "name_user": "171.79.88.152", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSee also)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saha_(surname)"}
{"title_page": "Regalecus russelii", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of oarfish}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Regalecus russelii Academia Sinica.jpg\n| image_caption = Taxidermied specimen of ''R. russelii'' in Academia Sinica, Taipei.\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Chordata]]\n| classis = [[Actinopterygii]]\n| ordo = [[Lampriformes]]\n| familia = [[Regalecidae]]\n| genus = [[Regalecus]]\n| species = '''''R. russelii'''''\n| binomial = ''Regalecus russelii''\n| binomial_authority = Cuvier, 1816\n}}\n\n'''''Regalecus russelii''''' is a species of [[oarfish]] in the family [[Regalecidae]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=272530|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Regalecus russelii (Cuvier, 1816)|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> ''Regalecus russelii'' or Russell's oarfish is a broadly-distributed marine fish, found in waters in the [[bathypelagic]] zone.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fishbase.us/summary/Regalecus-russelii.html|title=Regalecus russelii summary page|website=FishBase|language=en|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> ''R. russelii'' is a scaleless, elongate and ribbonlike fish, growing up to 8 meters in length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Regalecus russelii'' is a member of the fish genus [[Regalecus]] and oarfish family [[Regalecidae]]. The genus [[Regalecus]] currently includes only one other species of oarfish, ''[[Regalecus glesne]]''. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Lamp\" /> ''R. russelii'' is part of order [[Lampriformes]], which represents tube-eyes and ribbonfishes, and is part of the larger class of ray-finned fishes called [[Actinopterygii]]. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Anatomy and morphology ==\n''Regalecus russelii'' can grow up to 8 meters in length, and it has two [[dorsal fin]] crests that can reach 1 meter high.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''R. russelii'' can be distinguished by its red dorsal fin crests, light brown head, and scaleless, silver body. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Lamp\">{{cite journal |last1=Angulo |first1=A. |last2=L\u00f3pez-S\u00e1nchez |first2=M. I. |title=New records of lampriform fishes (Teleostei: Lampriformes) from the Pacific coast of lower Central America, with comments on the diversity, taxonomy and distribution of the Lampriformes in the eastern Pacific Ocean |journal=Zootaxa |date=2017 |volume=4236 |issue=3 |page=573-591 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.4236.3.11}}</ref> The body is covered by dermal [[tubercles]], which are concentrated along the ventral and lower side regions of the body. <ref name=\"Lamp\" /> Each dorsal fin has 333 to 371 [[Ray (fish fin anatomy)|rays]], which shorten and then become longer at the middle of the body.<ref name=\"Lamp\" /> <ref name=\":0\" />  Its [[pelvic fin]] contains more than three membranous appendages and is a single elongated ray.<ref name=\":0\" /> The stomach has a long [[caecum]], beginning posterior of the abdomen and extending to the end of the body.<ref name=\":0\" /> Muscle is contained in intermuscular [[Septum|septa]], with dorsal and ventral septa along with teleost\u2019s characteristic horizontal, vertical, and transverse septa.<ref name=\":0\" /> Older R. russelii often have a posterior stump-like tail, which is a consequence of [[self-amputation]] but show no signs of regeneration.<ref name=\":0\" /> In some specimens, this tail appears jagged and unhealed, consistent with a fresh self-amputation.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe majority of these fish have toothless jaws, but small vestigial teeth have been observed in some R. russelii. <ref name=\":0\" /> There are 113 to 122 vertebrae present in the spine of ''Regalecus russelii''. <ref name=\":0\" /> The skeleton of ''R. russelii'' contains distinct areas of [[hyperostosis]] that are most prominent on the dorsal [[pterygiophores]], but [[hyperostosis]] is also present on their [[cleithrum]] and along their supra[[occipital bone]].<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> The rest of their skeleton is cartilaginous. <ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> The [[hyperostosis]], or hyper-ossified bones, provide additional support to the pterygiophores during movement.<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> The presence of hyperostosis varies among ''R. russelii'' of different ages and sizes; hyperostosis is present in most large adult fish yet many smaller fish lack these regions of swollen bones.<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> ''R. russelii'''s flaccid skeleton lacks mineralization, which is advantageous in maintaining buoyancy in deep waters.<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\">{{cite journal |last1=Paig-Tran |first1=E.W. |last2=Barrios |first2=A.S. |last3=Ferry |first3=L.A. |title=Presence of repeating hyperostotic bones in dorsal pterygiophores of the oarfish, Regalecus russellii |journal=Journal of Anatomy |date=2016 |volume=229 |issue=4 |page=560-567 |doi=10.1111/joa.12503|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nOne of the few biological structures that has been studied is the [[otolith]], which is a structure in the inner ear that is involved in sensing movement and gravity. <ref name=\"Otolith\" /> ''R. russelii'' have very small sagittal otoliths that are difficult to observe; their small size may indicate that they play an insignificant role in sensing.<ref name=\"Otolith\" /> Researchers have been able to perform CT scans and rare, invasive studies on this structure of a deceased ''R. russelii'' to better understand its physiological significance.<ref name=\"Otolith\">{{cite journal |last1=Midway |first1=S.R. |last2=Wagner |first2=T. |title=The first description of oarfish (Regalecus russellii Cuvier 1816) (Regalecidae) ageing structures |journal=Journal of Applied Icthyology |date=2015 |volume=32 |issue=1 |page=113-116 |doi=10.1111/jai.12967}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\n''Regalecus russellii'' lives in deep waters near areas such as [[Japan]], [[California]], and [[Baja California]], in waters such as the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]], [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and [[Indian Ocean|Indian oceans]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Since 1901, there have been 19 verified sightings and strandings along the coast of California waters.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Feeney|first=Richard F.|last2=Lea|first2=Robert N.|date=December 2018|title=California Records of the Oarfish,Regalecus russelii(Cuvier, 1816) (Actinopterygii: Regalecidae)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.3160/3294.1|journal=Bulletin, Southern California Academy of Sciences|volume=117|issue=3|pages=169\u2013179|doi=10.3160/3294.1|issn=0038-3872}}</ref>\nThe ''R. russelii'' is found around the world equatorially, while the ''[[Regalecus glesne]]'' is found with [[antitropical distribution]]. <ref> {{cite journal |last1=Chakrabarty| first1=Prosanta| title= Systematics, Biology, and Distribution of the Species of the Oceanic Oarfish Genus Regalecus (Teleostei, Lampridiformes, Regalecidae)|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24635733?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents| journal= Copeia| date= 2013| volume=2013| issue=2| pages=336|issn= 00458511|}}</ref> The lack of live sightings of oarfish has made it difficult to determine the precise distribution of the ''Regalecus'' and further research is needed.\n\n== Feeding and diet ==\nIt uses a feeding stance to see the [[silhouette]] of its prey. It feeds on [[Krill|euphausiid]] crustaceans, small fishes and [[squid]], and uses its protrusile jaws to suck in prey.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> The oarfish mostly consumes a diet of krill  <ref> {{cite journal |last1=Poinar| first1=George|last2=Weinstein| first2=Sara| last3=Garcia-Vedrenne|first3=Ana|last4=Kuris|first4=Armand| title= First description of a nematode, Spinitectus gabata n. sp. (Spirurina: Cystidicolidae), from the deep sea oarfish, Regalecus russelii (Regalecidae) in Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sara_Weinstein/publication/272820870_First_description_of_a_nematode_Spinitectus_gabata_n_sp_Spirurina_Cystidicolidae_from_the_deep_sea_oarfish_Regalecus_russelii_Regalecidae_in_Japan/links/54efe2240cf2432ba657657a.pdf| journal= International Journal of Nematology| date= 2014| volume=24| issue=2| pages=117-123|}}</ref> as its energy source, using its jaw to fill its oro-branchial cavity with the crustaceans, that will then be held in the gullet and passed through.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fishbase.sinica.edu.tw/Summary/SpeciesSummary.php?id=25038|title=\"Regalicus russelii\"|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Conservation ==\nThere are no specific conservation measures for ''R. russellii'', and it occurs in at least one [[marine protected area]], and has been listed as '[[Least concern]]' by the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Mythology ==\nOarfishes, have been feared as \"the harbingers of earthquakes\" due to their sensitivity to weather patterns and strandings in California.<ref name=\":3\" /> Two deep sea oarfish were caught live in nets off the coast of Okinawa, Japan January 28, 2019. Both fish, however, died before making their way into an aquarium inland in the town Motobu. One fisher described the two oarfish squirming in the nets as looking like \u201creal dragons.\u201d A belief surrounds the species that they are \u201charbingers of earthquakes\u201d but there is no scientific evidence or an association established between recorded oarfish sightings and earthquakes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/02/17/national/rare-okinawa-oarfish-found-alive-eaten/|title=Okinawan fishermen reel in two live oarfish, eat portion of one|date=2019-02-17|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref> Spread through Japanese myth, the oarfish has been described as \u201cMessenger from the Sea God\u2019s Palace.\u201d Kiyoshi Wadatsumi, an expert in ecological seismology and director of e-PISCO, an organization which studies earthquakes, states that deep sea fish are more sensitive to the tectonic movements or tremors from active faults than fish closer to the surface of the ocean.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yamamoto|first=Daiki|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2010/03/06/national/sea-serpents-arrival-puzzling-or-portentous/|title=Sea serpents' arrival puzzling, or portentous?|date=2010-03-06|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n\n== Parasites==\n\n* ''[[Gymnorhadinorhynchus mariserpentis]]'' <small>Steinauer, Garcia-Vedrenne, Weinstein & Kuris, 2019</small>\n* ''[[Spinitectus gabata]]'' <small>Poinar, Weinstein, Garcia-Vedrenne & Kuris, 2014</small><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDespite the relatively limited number of oarfish researched, in 2014 scientists were able to discover a new species of nematode called Spinitectus gabata n. sp. (Spirurina: Cystidicolidae)  within the gastrointestinal tract of a R. Russelli off the coast of Japan. The S. gabata likely uses the krill that oarfish consumes as an intermediate host, since known Spinitectus species often involve crustaceans as intermediate hosts. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Poinar| first1=George|last2=Weinstein| first2=Sara| last3=Garcia-Vedrenne|first3=Ana|last4=Kuris|first4=Armand| title= First description of a nematode, Spinitectus gabata n. sp. (Spirurina: Cystidicolidae), from the deep sea oarfish, Regalecus russelii (Regalecidae) in Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sara_Weinstein/publication/272820870_First_description_of_a_nematode_Spinitectus_gabata_n_sp_Spirurina_Cystidicolidae_from_the_deep_sea_oarfish_Regalecus_russelii_Regalecidae_in_Japan/links/54efe2240cf2432ba657657a.pdf| journal= International Journal of Nematology| date= 2014| volume=24| issue=2| pages=117-123|}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5300744}}\n\n[[Category:Regalecidae]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1816]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of oarfish}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Regalecus russelii Academia Sinica.jpg\n| image_caption = Taxidermied specimen of ''R. russelii'' in Academia Sinica, Taipei.\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Chordata]]\n| classis = [[Actinopterygii]]\n| ordo = [[Lampriformes]]\n| familia = [[Regalecidae]]\n| genus = [[Regalecus]]\n| species = '''''R. russelii'''''\n| binomial = ''Regalecus russelii''\n| binomial_authority = Cuvier, 1816\n}}\n\n'''''Regalecus russelii''''' is a species of [[oarfish]] in the family [[Regalecidae]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=272530|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Regalecus russelii (Cuvier, 1816)|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> ''Regalecus russelii'' or Russell's oarfish is a broadly-distributed marine fish, found in waters in the [[bathypelagic]] zone.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fishbase.us/summary/Regalecus-russelii.html|title=Regalecus russelii summary page|website=FishBase|language=en|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> ''R. russelii'' is a scaleless, elongate and ribbonlike fish, growing up to 8 meters in length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Regalecus russelii'' is a member of the fish genus [[Regalecus]] and oarfish family [[Regalecidae]]. The genus [[Regalecus]] currently includes only one other species of oarfish, ''[[Regalecus glesne]]''. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Lamp\" /> ''R. russelii'' is part of order [[Lampriformes]], which represents tube-eyes and ribbonfishes, and is part of the larger class of ray-finned fishes called [[Actinopterygii]]. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Anatomy and morphology ==\n''Regalecus russelii'' can grow up to 8 meters in length, and it has two [[dorsal fin]] crests that can reach 1 meter high.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''R. russelii'' can be distinguished by its red dorsal fin crests, light brown head, and scaleless, silver body. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Lamp\">{{cite journal |last1=Angulo |first1=A. |last2=L\u00f3pez-S\u00e1nchez |first2=M. I. |title=New records of lampriform fishes (Teleostei: Lampriformes) from the Pacific coast of lower Central America, with comments on the diversity, taxonomy and distribution of the Lampriformes in the eastern Pacific Ocean |journal=Zootaxa |date=2017 |volume=4236 |issue=3 |page=573-591 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.4236.3.11}}</ref> The body is covered by dermal [[tubercles]], which are concentrated along the ventral and lower side regions of the body. <ref name=\"Lamp\" /> Each dorsal fin has 333 to 371 [[Ray (fish fin anatomy)|rays]], which shorten and then become longer at the middle of the body.<ref name=\"Lamp\" /> <ref name=\":0\" />  Its [[pelvic fin]] contains more than three membranous appendages and is a single elongated ray.<ref name=\":0\" /> The stomach has a long [[caecum]], beginning posterior of the abdomen and extending to the end of the body.<ref name=\":0\" /> Muscle is contained in intermuscular [[septa]], with dorsal and ventral septa along with teleost\u2019s characteristic horizontal, vertical, and transverse septa.<ref name=\":0\" /> Older R. russelii often have a posterior stump-like tail, which is a consequence of [[self-amputation]] but show no signs of regeneration.<ref name=\":0\" /> In some specimens, this tail appears jagged and unhealed, consistent with a fresh self-amputation.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe majority of these fish have toothless jaws, but small vestigial teeth have been observed in some R. russelii. <ref name=\":0\" /> There are 113 to 122 vertebrae present in the spine of ''Regalecus russelii''. <ref name=\":0\" /> The skeleton of ''R. russelii'' contains distinct areas of [[hyperostosis]] that are most prominent on the dorsal [[pterygiophores]], but [[hyperostosis]] is also present on their [[cleithrum]] and along their supra[[occipital bone]].<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> The rest of their skeleton is cartilaginous. <ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> The [[hyperostosis]], or hyper-ossified bones, provide additional support to the pterygiophores during movement.<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> The presence of hyperostosis varies among ''R. russelii'' of different ages and sizes; hyperostosis is present in most large adult fish yet many smaller fish lack these regions of swollen bones.<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\" /> ''R. russelii'''s flaccid skeleton lacks mineralization, which is advantageous in maintaining buoyancy in deep waters.<ref name=\"Hyperostotic\">{{cite journal |last1=Paig-Tran |first1=E.W. |last2=Barrios |first2=A.S. |last3=Ferry |first3=L.A. |title=Presence of repeating hyperostotic bones in dorsal pterygiophores of the oarfish, Regalecus russellii |journal=Journal of Anatomy |date=2016 |volume=229 |issue=4 |page=560-567 |doi=10.1111/joa.12503|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nOne of the few biological structures that has been studied is the [[otolith]], which is a structure in the inner ear that is involved in sensing movement and gravity. <ref name=\"Otolith\" /> ''R. russelii'' have very small sagittal otoliths that are difficult to observe; their small size may indicate that they play an insignificant role in sensing.<ref name=\"Otolith\" /> Researchers have been able to perform CT scans and rare, invasive studies on this structure of a deceased ''R. russelii'' to better understand its physiological significance.<ref name=\"Otolith\">{{cite journal |last1=Midway |first1=S.R. |last2=Wagner |first2=T. |title=The first description of oarfish (Regalecus russellii Cuvier 1816) (Regalecidae) ageing structures |journal=Journal of Applied Icthyology |date=2015 |volume=32 |issue=1 |page=113-116 |doi=10.1111/jai.12967}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\n''Regalecus russellii'' lives in deep waters near areas such as [[Japan]], [[California]], and [[Baja California]], in waters such as the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]], [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and [[Indian Ocean|Indian oceans]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Since 1901, there have been 19 verified sightings and strandings along the coast of California waters.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Feeney|first=Richard F.|last2=Lea|first2=Robert N.|date=December 2018|title=California Records of the Oarfish,Regalecus russelii(Cuvier, 1816) (Actinopterygii: Regalecidae)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.3160/3294.1|journal=Bulletin, Southern California Academy of Sciences|volume=117|issue=3|pages=169\u2013179|doi=10.3160/3294.1|issn=0038-3872}}</ref>\nThe ''R. russelii'' is found around the world equatorially, while the ''[[Regalecus glesne]]'' is found with [[antitropical distribution]]. <ref> {{cite journal |last1=Chakrabarty| first1=Prosanta| title= Systematics, Biology, and Distribution of the Species of the Oceanic Oarfish Genus Regalecus (Teleostei, Lampridiformes, Regalecidae)|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24635733?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents| journal= Copeia| date= 2013| volume=2013| issue=2| pages=336|issn= 00458511|}}</ref> The lack of live sightings of oarfish has made it difficult to determine the precise distribution of the ''Regalecus'' and further research is needed.\n\n== Feeding and diet ==\nIt uses a feeding stance to see the [[silhouette]] of its prey. It feeds on [[Krill|euphausiid]] crustaceans, small fishes and [[squid]], and uses its protrusile jaws to suck in prey.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> The oarfish mostly consumes a diet of krill  <ref> {{cite journal |last1=Poinar| first1=George|last2=Weinstein| first2=Sara| last3=Garcia-Vedrenne|first3=Ana|last4=Kuris|first4=Armand| title= First description of a nematode, Spinitectus gabata n. sp. (Spirurina: Cystidicolidae), from the deep sea oarfish, Regalecus russelii (Regalecidae) in Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sara_Weinstein/publication/272820870_First_description_of_a_nematode_Spinitectus_gabata_n_sp_Spirurina_Cystidicolidae_from_the_deep_sea_oarfish_Regalecus_russelii_Regalecidae_in_Japan/links/54efe2240cf2432ba657657a.pdf| journal= International Journal of Nematology| date= 2014| volume=24| issue=2| pages=117-123|}}</ref> as its energy source, using its jaw to fill its oro-branchial cavity with the crustaceans, that will then be held in the gullet and passed through.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fishbase.sinica.edu.tw/Summary/SpeciesSummary.php?id=25038|title=\"Regalicus russelii\"|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Conservation ==\nThere are no specific conservation measures for ''R. russellii'', and it occurs in at least one [[marine protected area]], and has been listed as '[[Least concern]]' by the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Mythology ==\nOarfishes, have been feared as \"the harbingers of earthquakes\" due to their sensitivity to weather patterns and strandings in California.<ref name=\":3\" /> Two deep sea oarfish were caught live in nets off the coast of Okinawa, Japan January 28, 2019. Both fish, however, died before making their way into an aquarium inland in the town Motobu. One fisher described the two oarfish squirming in the nets as looking like \u201creal dragons.\u201d A belief surrounds the species that they are \u201charbingers of earthquakes\u201d but there is no scientific evidence or an association established between recorded oarfish sightings and earthquakes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/02/17/national/rare-okinawa-oarfish-found-alive-eaten/|title=Okinawan fishermen reel in two live oarfish, eat portion of one|date=2019-02-17|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref> Spread through Japanese myth, the oarfish has been described as \u201cMessenger from the Sea God\u2019s Palace.\u201d Kiyoshi Wadatsumi, an expert in ecological seismology and director of e-PISCO, an organization which studies earthquakes, states that deep sea fish are more sensitive to the tectonic movements or tremors from active faults than fish closer to the surface of the ocean.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yamamoto|first=Daiki|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2010/03/06/national/sea-serpents-arrival-puzzling-or-portentous/|title=Sea serpents' arrival puzzling, or portentous?|date=2010-03-06|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n\n== Parasites==\n\n* ''[[Gymnorhadinorhynchus mariserpentis]]'' <small>Steinauer, Garcia-Vedrenne, Weinstein & Kuris, 2019</small>\n* ''[[Spinitectus gabata]]'' <small>Poinar, Weinstein, Garcia-Vedrenne & Kuris, 2014</small><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDespite the relatively limited number of oarfish researched, in 2014 scientists were able to discover a new species of nematode called Spinitectus gabata n. sp. (Spirurina: Cystidicolidae)  within the gastrointestinal tract of a R. Russelli off the coast of Japan. The S. gabata likely uses the krill that oarfish consumes as an intermediate host, since known Spinitectus species often involve crustaceans as intermediate hosts. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Poinar| first1=George|last2=Weinstein| first2=Sara| last3=Garcia-Vedrenne|first3=Ana|last4=Kuris|first4=Armand| title= First description of a nematode, Spinitectus gabata n. sp. (Spirurina: Cystidicolidae), from the deep sea oarfish, Regalecus russelii (Regalecidae) in Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sara_Weinstein/publication/272820870_First_description_of_a_nematode_Spinitectus_gabata_n_sp_Spirurina_Cystidicolidae_from_the_deep_sea_oarfish_Regalecus_russelii_Regalecidae_in_Japan/links/54efe2240cf2432ba657657a.pdf| journal= International Journal of Nematology| date= 2014| volume=24| issue=2| pages=117-123|}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5300744}}\n\n[[Category:Regalecidae]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1816]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSepta(link changed toSeptum) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regalecus_russelii"}
{"title_page": "Touch Football World Cup", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports league\n| title           = Touch Rugby World Cup\n| current_season  = \n| last_season     = 2019\n| upcoming_season = 2023\n| sport           = Touch Football\n| logo            = \n| founded         = 1988\n| inaugural       = 1988\n| teams           = 28\n| countries       = Australia, Belgium, Chile, China, Chinese Taipei, Cook Islands, England, Europe, France, Fiji, Germany, Great Britain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Italy, Japan, Malaysia, Netherlands, New Zealand, Niue, Papua New Guinea, Philippines, Samoa, Scotland, Singapore, South Africa, United Arab Emirates, United States, Wales\n| champion        = Australia\n| champ_season    = 2019\n| most_champs     = \n| most successful club = \n| tournament_format = Round Robin and a Finals Series\n| website         = https://www.internationaltouch.org/\n}}\n\nThe first [[Touch football (rugby league)|Touch Football]] World Cup tournament was held in 1988. Touch football and the Touch football world cup are monitored by the international governing body for touch the FIT (Federation of International Touch).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationaltouch.org/|title=Federation of International Touch|website=www.internationaltouch.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The Touch world cup has been hosted in five continents (Asia, Oceania, Europe, North America, Africa) but is yet to be played in South America. Australia has hosted the World Cup the most having hosted it thrice. While the number of participant teams is growing steadily, almost all finals to date have been contested between Australia and New Zealand. Australia has won the most finals.\n\nTouch as included in the Touch world cup is played on a rectangular 70m x 50m pitch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationaltouch.org/media/AboutFIT/Evolution%20of%20Touch%20(23-12-10).pdf|title=Evolution of Touch|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It is played six aside with eight substitutes. The match is played for 40 minutes in two twenty-minute halves. Touch unlike many other football variants always uses three referees and this is the same in the Touch football world cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.warriorsrugby.com/touch-rugby-rules/|title=Touch Rugby Rules|website=Utah Warriors Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n[[File:NRL Rugby League field.svg|thumb|A rugby league field, similarly used in touch with 70 metres not 100 metres in length.]]\nTouch football and therefore the Touch World Cup are seen as competitors to its [[Rugby union|Rugby Union]] equivalent, [[Tag rugby]] and the Tag rugby world cup, which is held every three years, the Touch Rugby World Cup is instead held every four years much like the football and rugby (league and union) world cups.\n\n==World Cup Venues==\nThe following outlines the World Cups held and planned for the future\n* 1988 - Australia ([[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]])\n* 1991 - New Zealand ([[Auckland]])\n* 1995 - United States ([[Hawaii]])\n* 1999 - Australia ([[Sydney]])\n* 2003 - Japan ([[Kumagaya]])\n* 2007 - [[South Africa]] ([[Stellenbosch]])\n* 2011 - Scotland ([[Edinburgh]])\n* 2015 - Australia ([[Coffs Harbour]])\n* 2019 - Malaysia ([[Putrajaya]])\n*2023-TBD\n\n==World Cup Results==\n\n===1988 - Australia (Gold Coast)===\nWorld Cup # : 1<br />\nDates : 14\u201316 November 1988<br />\nParticipants : 5 (Australia, Canada, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, USA)<br/>\nLocation : [[Carrara Oval]], [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]], Australia<br/>\n'''Overall winner : Australia''' \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+\n! Division!! Winners !! Runners-Up !! Teams\n|-\n|Men's Open || Australia || New Zealand || 4\n|-\n|Women's Open || Australia || New Zealand || 4\n|-\n|Mixed Open || Australia || New Zealand || 4\n|-\n|Men's Masters (Over 35 years)|| Australia || New Zealand || 5\n|-\n|}\n\n===1991 - New Zealand (Auckland)===\nWo