14-0&a=COMPS| title=Draws and Results| publisher=Touch World Cup 2015}}</ref>!! Runners-Up !! Teams\n|-\n|Men's Open || Australia || New Zealand || 16\n|-\n|Women's Open || Australia || New Zealand || 14\n|-\n|Mixed Open || Australia || New Zealand || 22\n|-\n|Women's Over 27 Years || Australia || New Zealand || 5\n|-\n|Senior Mixed || Australia || New Zealand || 6\n|-\n|Men's Over 30 Years|| Australia || Cook Islands || 7\n|-\n|Men's Over 35 Years|| New Zealand || Australia || 6\n|-\n|Men's Over 40 Years|| Australia || New Zealand || 9\n|-\n|Men's Over 50 Years|| Australia || Italy || 5\n|-\n|}\n\n====Squads====\n{{Main|2015 Touch Football World Cup squads}}\n\nThe competition featured ninety teams from twenty five participating nations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-04-30/world27s-best-touch-footballers-descend-on-coffs-harbour/6433268 |title=World's best touch footballers descend on Coffs Harbour |author=Tom Lowrey |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/touch-world-cup-officially-launched/tabid/10874/newsid/85646/default.aspx |title=Touch World Cup officially launched |author=NRL.com |date=24 April 2015 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2019 - World Cup (Malaysia,Putrajaya)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationaltouch.org/events/world-cup/2019/|title=Federation of International Touch - World Cup - 2019|website=www.internationaltouch.org|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref>===\nWorld Cup # : 9<br />\nDates : 29 April - 4 May 2019<br />\nParticipants : 28 (Australia, Belgium, Chile, China, Chinese Taipei, Cook Islands, England, Europe, France, Fiji, Germany, Great Britain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Italy, Japan, Malaysia, Netherlands, New Zealand, Niue, Papua New Guinea, Philippines, Samoa, Scotland, Singapore, South Africa, United Arab Emirates, United States, Wales)<br />\nLocation : Taman Ekuestrian, [[Putrajaya]], [[Malaysia]]<br />\n'''Overall winner : Australia''' \n\n'''Overall Runners up : New Zealand''' \n[[File:Flag of Australia (Brighter).svg|thumb|Overall Winners, Australia]]\n[[File:Flag of New Zealand.svg|thumb|Overall Runners Up, New Zealand]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+\n! Division!! Winners<ref name=\":0\" />!! Runners-Up \n!3rd Place!! Teams\n|-\n|Men's Open || Australia || New Zealand \n|Japan|| 16\n|-\n|Women's Open || Australia || New Zealand \n|Japan|| 17\n|-\n|Mixed Open || Australia || New Zealand \n|Scotland|| 22\n|-\n|Women's Over 27 Years || New Zealand || Australia \n|England|| 7\n|-\n|Senior Mixed (over 30 years) || Australia || Cook Islands \n|New Zealand|| 11\n|-\n|Men's Over 30 Years|| Australia || South Africa \n|France|| 8\n|-\n|Men's Over 35 Years|| Australia || New Zealand \n|Cook Islands|| 6\n|-\n|Women's Over 35 Years\n|Australia\n|New Zealand\n|England\n|4\n|-\n|Men's Over 40 Years|| New Zealand || Australia \n|Japan|| 13\n|-\n|Men's Over 45 Years\n|Australia\n|New Zealand\n|South Africa\n|6\n|-\n|Men's Over 50 Years|| New Zealand || Australia \n|Singapore|| 6\n|-\n|}\n\nThe 2019 Touch Football World Cup is the latest edition of the Touch football world cup. All divisions consisted of a round robin of 1 or more groups, and a finals series. Some groups also consisted of a playoff series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationaltouch.org/events/world-cup/2019/|title=Federation of International Touch - World Cup - 2019|website=www.internationaltouch.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n\n== External links ==   \n*[http://www.touchworldcup2011.co.uk/ 2011 World Cup website]\n\n{{Main world cups}}\n\n[[Category:Touch competitions]]\n[[Category:World championships in football variants|Touch]]\n[[Category:World cups]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Annual sporting events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports league\n| title           = Touch Rugby World Cup\n| current_season  = \n| last_season     = 2019\n| upcoming_season = 2023\n| sport           = Touch Football\n| logo            = \n| founded         = 1988\n| inaugural       = 1988\n| teams           = 28\n| countries       = Australia, Belgium, Chile, China, Chinese Taipei, Cook Islands, England, Europe, France, Fiji, Germany, Great Britain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Italy, Japan, Malaysia, Netherlands, New Zealand, Niue, Papua New Guinea, Philippines, Samoa, Scotland, Singapore, South Africa, United Arab Emirates, United States, Wales\n| champion        = Australia\n| champ_season    = 2019\n| most_champs     = \n| most successful club = \n| tournament_format = Round Robin and a Finals Series\n| website         = https://www.internationaltouch.org/\n}}\n\nThe first [[Touch football (rugby league)|Touch Football]] World Cup tournament was held in 1988. Touch football and the Touch football world cup are monitored by the international governing body for touch the FIT (Federation of International Touch).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationaltouch.org/|title=Federation of International Touch|website=www.internationaltouch.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The Touch world cup has been hosted in five continents (Asia,Oceania,Europe,North America,Africa) but is yet to be played in South America. Australia has hosted the World Cup the most having hosted it thrice. While the number of participant teams is growing steadily, almost all finals to date have been contested between Australia and New Zealand. And of most finals Australia has won the most.\n\nTouch as included in the Touch world cup is played on a rectangular 70m x 50m pitch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationaltouch.org/media/AboutFIT/Evolution%20of%20Touch%20(23-12-10).pdf|title=Evolution of Touch|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It is played six aside with eight substitutes. The match is played for 40 minutes in two twenty-minute halves. Touch unlike many other football variants always uses three referees and this is the same in the Touch football world cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.warriorsrugby.com/touch-rugby-rules/|title=Touch Rugby Rules|website=Utah Warriors Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n[[File:NRL Rugby League field.svg|thumb|A rugby league field, similarly used in touch with 70 metres not 100 metres in length.]]\nTouch football and therefore the Touch World Cup are seen as competitors to its [[Rugby union|Rugby Union]] equivalent, [[Tag rugby]] and the Tag rugby world cup, which is held every three years, the Touch Rugby World Cup is instead held every four years much like the football and rugby (league and union) world cups.\n\n==World Cup Venues==\nThe following outlines the World Cups held and planned for the future\n* 1988 - Australia ([[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]])\n* 1991 - New Zealand ([[Auckland]])\n* 1995 - United States ([[Hawaii]])\n* 1999 - Australia ([[Sydney]])\n* 2003 - Japan ([[Kumagaya]])\n* 2007 - [[South Africa]] ([[Stellenbosch]])\n* 2011 - Scotland ([[Edinburgh]])\n* 2015 - Australia ([[Coffs Harbour]])\n* 2019 - Malaysia ([[Putrajaya]])\n*2023-TBD\n\n==World Cup Results==\n\n===1988 - Australia (Gold Coast)===\nWorld Cup # : 1<br />\nDates : 14\u201316 November 1988<br />\nParticipants : 5 (Australia, Canada, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, USA)<br/>\nLocation : [[Carrara Oval]], [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]], Australia<br/>\n'''Overall winner : Australia''' \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+\n! Division!! Winners !! Runners-Up !! Teams\n|-\n|Men's Open || Australia || New Zealand || 4\n|-\n|Women's Open || Australia || New Zealand || 4\n|-\n|Mixed Open || Australia || New Zealand || 4\n|-\n|Men's Masters (Over 35 years)|| Australia || New Zealand || 5\n|-\n|}\n\n===1991 - New Zealand (Auckland)===\nWorld Cup # : 2<br />\nDates : 3\u20137 December 1991<br />\nParticipants : 9 (Australia, Cook Islands, Fiji, Japan, New Zealand, Niue, Papua New Guinea, Samoa, Tokelau)<br